  RFC9543 [label="RFC9543
A Framework for Network Slices in
Networks Built from IETF Technologies
2024", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC9543.html", target="_top", tooltip="This document describes network slicing in the context of networks built from IETF technologies. It defines the term IETF Network Slice to describe this type of network slice and establishes the general principles of network slicing in the IETF context. The document discusses the general framework for requesting and operating IETF Network Slices, the characteristics of an IETF Network Slice, the necessary system components and interfaces, and the mapping of abstract requests to more specific technologies. The document also discusses related considerations with monitoring and security. This document also provides definitions of related terms to enable consistent usage in other IETF documents that describe or use aspects of IETF Network Slices."];
  cites -> RFC9543;
  RFC4026 [label="RFC4026
Provider Provisioned Virtual Private
Network (VPN) Terminology
2005", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC4026.html", target="_top", tooltip="The widespread interest in provider-provisioned Virtual Private Network (VPN) solutions lead to memos proposing different and overlapping solutions. The IETF working groups (first Provider Provisioned VPNs and later Layer 2 VPNs and Layer 3 VPNs) have discussed these proposals and documented specifications. This has lead to the development of a partially new set of concepts used to describe the set of VPN services. To a certain extent, more than one term covers the same concept, and sometimes the same term covers more than one concept. This document seeks to make the terminology in the area clearer and more intuitive. This memo provides information for the Internet community."];
  cites -> RFC4026;
  RFC7665 [label="RFC7665
Service Function Chaining (SFC)
Architecture
2015", shape=ellipse, URL="RFC7665.html", target="_top", tooltip="This document describes an architecture for the specification, creation, and ongoing maintenance of Service Function Chains (SFCs) in a network.  It includes architectural concepts, principles, and components used in the construction of composite services through deployment of SFCs, with a focus on those to be standardized in the IETF.  This document does not propose solutions, protocols, or extensions to existing protocols."];
